            <h1 class="syntax_textcolor">1) What is Variable?</h1>
            <p>* <b class="syntax_textcolor">Variables</b> are containers for storing data values.</p>
            <p>* In <b class="syntax_textcolor">Variables</b> for any datatype if we allocate second value for variable it will give output as second value not first value.except 'const'</p>
            <p>* All C# <b class="syntax_textcolor">Variables</b> must be identified with unique names.These unique names are called identifiers.</p>
            <p>* Identifiers can be short names (like x and y) or more descriptive names (age, sum, totalVolume).</p><br /><br /><hr />



            <h1 class="syntax_textcolor">2) Variable Syntax : </h1>
            <h2 > <b class="syntax_textcolor">String</b> (DataType)  <b class="syntax_textcolor">myVar</b> (variableName)  = <b class="syntax_textcolor">Prithvi </b> (value) ;</h2><br /><br /><hr />


            <h1>3) Rules for naming Variables : </h1>
            <ul>
                <li>Names can contain <b class="syntax_textcolor">letters, digits and the underscore character (_)</b>.</li>
                <li>Names must begin with a <b class="syntax_textcolor">letter or underscore</b>.</li>
                <li>Names should start with a <b class="syntax_textcolor">lowercase letter</b> and it cannot contain <b class="syntax_textcolor">whitespace</b>.</li>
                <li>Names are <b class="syntax_textcolor">case sensitive</b> ("myVar" and "myvar" are different variables).</li>
                <li>Reserved words (like C# keywords, such as int or double) cannot be used as names</li>
            </ul>
